    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston S.C.</placeName>
                <date>April 20<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1830</date>.</p>
            <p><addressee>Revd. Mr. Leeser</addressee>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I was not misrepresented to you<lb/> when you were told I entertain
                “feelings of Friendship;”<lb/> and I am pleased in the opportunity thus offered,
                of<lb/> renewing to you, the assurance of the most unfeigned<lb/> sentiments of
                Friendly concern, for your prosperity and<lb/> advancement, without using high toned
                expressions, you<lb/> have claims to the regard of every man who<lb/> venerates the
                religion of his forefathers, and your<lb/> individual merits entitle you to the
                consideration<lb/> of those who possess your acquaintance.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I shall cheerfully use my efforts to further<lb/> your views in
                obtaining subscribers to your contemplated<lb/> Publications, and doubt not they
                will meet with<lb/> deserved approbation. I have placed one of<lb/> the Properties
                in the hands of a respectable book<lb/> seller who will use all exertions to obtain
                subscribers<lb/> not of our <sic>pursuasion</sic>—and he intends also to make<lb/>
                it more public by placing it in the Gazette of our<lb/> city, provided it is
                agreeable to you. I cannot<lb/> promise you many subscribers among our people.<lb/>
                I find that the subscription lists you sent<lb/> to other of your Friends are in
                circulation, and<lb/> will interfere with the number of subscribers, the</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I should have otherwise obtained—however, I<lb/> shall do all I can for you. Why was
                your title<lb/> of Revd not prefixed to your name? I hope your<lb/> modesty did not
                prompt to the omissions.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It is sometime since I have heard from<lb/>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, it is always a source of pleasure to<lb/> hear
                of my Friends through any channel. I hope<lb/> they are all well particularly the
                young Ladies,<lb/> to whom you will please make my best respects<lb/> acceptable.
                By-the-By, have you made a selection?<lb/>
                <sic>and</sic> is your admiration of the Lady you name<lb/> in your letter, still as
                strong as when I last was<lb/> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>? I have always
                considered it as<lb/> perfectly consistent with clerical Gentlemen, to pay
                their<lb/> adorations to a superior and Inferior <hi rend="underline"
                    >Divinities</hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I contemplate, should professional concerns not<lb/> interfere, to
                pay you a short visit some time during<lb/> the summer, till which I have the
                pleasure</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">of subscribing myself</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">your friend and</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">well wisher</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Jacob De La Motta</persName>
            </p>
            <p>P. S. My best respects to<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Peixotto</persName> and his family.</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>The <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>per packet</p>
            <p>
                <persName>Langdon Chaves<add>?</add></persName>
            </p>
